        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down. | Beckenham. Kent.</placeName>
                    <date>April 19</date>
                    <salute>My dear M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Crawley.</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Pray thank your Father sincerely for me for having sent so venerable a Relic—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> It is characteristic how much more most of us consider our superiors than our inferiors, that I remember more or less almost every boy above me or in the same form &amp; very few of those below me in the school.</p>
<p>I am very much obliged to you for your translation which seems to me Capital—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I fear as snapping the fingers here means being puzzled &amp; not contempt, it will not serve my purpose— But “he has pillared his chin upon his hand” will come in under puzzled meditation.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>With my best thanks. | Yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin.</p>
<p>Frank is gone to Chatham for the Engineers Ball.<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to the Engineers’ Ball (see n. 4, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8291.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Charles Crawley, [18 April 1872]</ref> and n. 2. The venerable relic was a list of pupils at Shrewsbury School.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8291.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Charles Crawley, [18 April 1872]</ref> and n. 3. In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2400.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi></ref>, p. 230, CD quoted these words from the passage of Plautus’s <hi rend="italic">Miles gloriosus</hi> that Crawley had translated for him.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Brompton Barracks in Chatham is the headquarters of the Corps of Royal Engineers. <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin’s</ref> brother Leonard was commissioned in the Royal Engineers in January 1871 (RMAS archives, Sandhurst collection). A grand ball was held on 18 April 1872 at the barracks (<hi rend="italic">The Times</hi>, 20 April 1872, p. 5).</note>
        </div>        
            
